  "stimulus": "Let $R$ be the region in the first quadrant enclosed by the graphs of $y = 2x$ and $y = x^2$, as shown in the figure.",
  "stimulus_image": null,
  "documents": null,
  "parts": [
    {
      "letter": "a",
      "prompt": "Find the area of $R$.",
      "point_value": 3,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: Area $= \\int_0^2(2x - x^2)\\, dx = \\left[x^2 - \\frac{x^3}{3}\\right]_0^2 = 4 - \\frac{8}{3} = \\frac{4}{3}$.",
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "a1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct integrand",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct integrand"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\int_0^2 (2x - x^2)\\, dx$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct antiderivative",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct antiderivative"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\left[x^2 - \\frac{x^3}{3}\\right]_0^2$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct answer",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct answer"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$4 - \\frac{8}{3} = \\frac{4}{3}$"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "b",
      "prompt": "The region $R$ is the base of a solid. For this solid, at each $x$ the cross section perpendicular to the $x$-axis has area $A(x) = \\sin\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}x\\right)$. Find the volume of the solid.",
      "point_value": 3,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: Volume $= \\int_0^2 \\sin\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}x\\right)\\, dx = \\left[-\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi x}{2}\\right)\\right]_0^2 = \\frac{4}{\\pi}$.",
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "b1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct integrand",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct integrand"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\int_0^2 \\sin\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}x\\right)\\, dx$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "b2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct antiderivative",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct antiderivative"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\left[-\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{2}x\\right)\\right]_0^2$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "b3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct answer",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct answer"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$-\\frac{2}{\\pi}\\cos(\\pi) + \\frac{2}{\\pi}\\cos(0) = \\frac{2}{\\pi} + \\frac{2}{\\pi} = \\frac{4}{\\pi}$"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "c",
      "prompt": "Another solid has the same base $R$. For this solid, the cross sections perpendicular to the $y$-axis are squares. Write, but do not evaluate, an integral expression for the volume of the solid.",
      "point_value": 3,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: Volume $= \\int_0^4 \\left(\\sqrt{y} - \\frac{y}{2}\\right)^2\\, dy$ (do not evaluate).",
